<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> The Art of Beginning<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.80)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/swtcg/main/mpage.php?member=10783'>Mathew "JaWookie" Rodgers</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/swtcg/main/mpage.php?member=10783&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 15, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">   While in college I took a theatre course.  In this class I studied the history of Theatre and read many plays.  My professor had a saying he used often that has always stuck with me.  &quot;Great is the Art of Beginning,&quot; he would say.  He taught me that the beginning is vital to the success of any dramatic work.<br>
<br>
  So it is with the new Star Wars TCG.  The designers at Wizards of the Coast have created a powerful and elegant game mechanic to begin this game.  Now, this game is very new and I have only played about 25 games, but I am so pleased with this Setup mechanic that I wanted to share some of my thoughts about it on this site.<br>
<br>
  In this article I will share 3 observations about the Setup and how to make the right plays in order to create your best chance for success.<br>
<br>
1) The 30 Point Foundation<br>
<br>
  In the Star Wars TCG there are two forms of resources available to you each turn to play cards from your hand.  One is fixed (Force) and the other is random (Build Points).  The Setup is the only time you have a fixed amount of build points.  How you spend these points is vital to your success.  <br>
<br>
  When you construct your deck you employ strategy (higher level, more broad).  As soon as you begin the Setup, you move to the level of tactics (specific and immediate).  The entire game is built off of the foundation you create during Setup.  Once that foundation is gone, you are left with only the roll of the dice for Build Points and what cards you can get into hand.  <br>
<br>
  Each of those 30 points are more precious than gold, do not squander them.  Calculate the possible combinations available to you every step of the way.  Look at the Setup not as one block of 30 points, but rather as three blocks of 10 points.  This way the Setup has s beginning, middle and end.  Use the Setup to &#8220;SET UP&#8221; your opponent.  Plot what you&#8217;re going to do in the beginning, middle and end.  Have a goal in mind.  How do you want your opponent to react to you?  What is the overall result you expect to see from your deck design once Setup is complete?<br>
<br>
  Work to balance the elements of strategy and tactics, in this you will find success.<br>
<br>
2) Options, Options, Options<br>
<br>
  Trading Card Games are about card advantage.  If you have more options than your opponent, you are in a superior position (doesn&#8217;t mean you will always win &#8211; you still have to play well, of course).  However, in the Star Wars TCG Setup, card advantage can spell victory or doom.<br>
<br>
  Try this: keep the cost of the early cards you play low.  This will allow you to draw more cards into your hand during Setup and give you more options.  I have begun to see a pattern in my own play here.  When playing Dark Side, I do not play a unit with a cost greater than 3 points as my opening card, unless I have no other option.<br>
<br>
  Try this also: whenever possible, only exceed your opponent&#8217;s build cost total by one point.  This will help you get as many cards out as possible.  When playing Light Side, like the example above, I aim to exceed the Dark Side player&#8217;s cost by only one point, thereby seeking card advantage.<br>
<br>
  Sometimes your options are limited due to your initial draw.  This is, of course, part of the way card games play.  However, your opponent doesn&#8217;t know that you don&#8217;t have any ground cards in your hand.  So, yet again, even more reason to potentially play less expensive units in order to keep your options open.  Ultimately, your decisions during Setup are based on your deck construction, what you perceive your opponent to be doing and what options you have in your hand.  So keep your options open.<br>
<br>
3) Potential vs. Performers<br>
<br>
  There are several elements to this game that are random (what cards you draw, how many build points your get and how many hits you can score during battle).  The challenge is creating the best possible chance to succeed.  When creating this chance, ask yourself this: Is the card you are playing a card with great potential or is it a great performer?  Being able to answer this question is vital.<br>
<br>
  Cards with potential are ones that have specific abilities or stats that are great if the conditions are right.  <br>
<br>
  The Droid Control Ship is one example.  It has great potential because it gives all droids +10 Speed and it has 9 Power and 9 Health.  However, it is very slow (10 Speed) and expensive (9 Build Points).  Not to mention that all those speedy little droids take 1 damage if the Control Ship is discarded from the Space Arena.  9 Power is a lot of dice, but it does you no good if you don&#8217;t get to use it.  But, it&#8217;s got 9 Health, right? Well, there&#8217;s nothing like seeing your Droid Control Ship vaporized before your very eyes in the first turn of the game (trust me, it can happen). <br>
<br>
  Cards that are performers are ones that work for you game after game, no matter what the situation.  These cards are a great value for their cost.<br>
<br>
  Look at the Bravo N-1 Starfighter.  It costs 3 Build Points, it is fast (50 Speed), and has 3 Power with the added bonus of Critical Hit 1.  This is a great performer.  You are going to get this card into play and it is going to perform for you.  Now, add R2-D2 and a well played Surge of Power and you get one mean machine &#8211; ouch!<br>
<br>
  The key is to balance your deck with the right amount of potentials and performers.   Think about your risks and how the card is going to get you closer to winning the game.  If you play cards with great potential during your Setup, don&#8217;t be surprised if your opponent simply retreats and lets your 15 build points of cards just sit there while they start pounding you in the other two arenas.<br>
 <br>
  I hope these three topics have given you some &#8220;food for thought.&#8221;  There is much more that I would like to write about the Setup (I had to edit this article down quite a bit to keep it small).  Perhaps I will write a part two.<br>
<br>
So, good luck Padawan (or is it Apprentice?).<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
